- Dashboard terasa native-app

React Hooks Rules & Performance Optimization (CRITICAL)
- **CRITICAL**: Semua optimisasi performance HARUS mengikuti Rules of Hooks. Pelanggaran akan menyebabkan error runtime.

1. **Rules of Hooks - NEVER Violate**
   - **NEVER** call hooks conditionally (inside if statements, loops, or nested functions).
   - **NEVER** call hooks inside JSX (props, render functions, etc.).
   - **ALWAYS** call all hooks at the top level of component, before any early returns.
   - **ALWAYS** call hooks in the same order on every render.
   
   ❌ BAD - Hook di dalam JSX:
   ```tsx
   <SplitViewSidebar
     renderItem={useCallback((item) => <ItemCard item={item} />, [])}  // ❌ Hook di dalam JSX prop
   />
   ```
   
   ❌ BAD - Hook setelah early return:
   ```tsx
   export function Component() {
     if (!hasPermission) {
       return <NoPermission />;  // ❌ Early return sebelum hooks
     }
     const data = useQuery(...);  // ❌ Hook dipanggil setelah early return
   }
   ```
   
   ✅ GOOD - Hook di top level, sebelum early return:
   ```tsx
   export function Component() {
     // Semua hooks dipanggil di top level
     const data = useQuery(...);
     const hasPermission = useHasPermission("VIEW");
     const handleClick = useCallback(() => {}, []);
     const memoizedValue = useMemo(() => compute(), [deps]);
     
     // Early return SETELAH semua hooks
     if (!hasPermission) {
       return <NoPermission />;
     }
     
     // RenderItem callback dipanggil di top level, bukan di JSX
     const renderItem = useCallback((item) => (
       <ItemCard item={item} />
     ), []);
     
     return (
       <SplitViewSidebar renderItem={renderItem} />
     );
   }
   ```

2. **useMemo & useCallback - Stable Dependencies**
   - **ALWAYS** ensure dependency arrays are stable and consistent across renders.
   - **NEVER** include function references that change on every render unless wrapped in useCallback.
   - **ALWAYS** include all dependencies that are used inside the memoized value/callback.
   
   ❌ BAD - Dependency array berubah-ubah:
   ```tsx
   const columns = useMemo(() => [
     { accessor: (row) => getStatusBadge(row.status) }
   ], [getStatusBadge, hasPermission, handleClick, mutation.isPending]);  // ❌ Bisa berubah urutan/ukuran
   ```
   
   ✅ GOOD - Stable dependencies dengan useCallback:
   ```tsx
   // Stabilkan function references dulu
   const getStatusBadge = useCallback((status) => { /* ... */ }, [t]);
   const handleClick = useCallback((id) => { /* ... */ }, []);
   
   // Baru gunakan di useMemo dengan dependencies yang stabil
   const columns = useMemo(() => [
     { accessor: (row) => getStatusBadge(row.status) }
   ], [getStatusBadge, hasPermission, handleClick, mutation.isPending]);
   ```

3. **React.memo untuk Component Optimization**
   - Gunakan `React.memo` untuk component yang sering re-render tapi props jarang berubah.
   - **ALWAYS** provide custom comparison function untuk complex props.
   - **NEVER** wrap component yang props-nya selalu berubah (akan sia-sia).
   
   ✅ GOOD - Memoized component dengan custom comparison:
   ```tsx
   const ItemCard = memo(({ item, getStatusBadge }: Props) => {
     return <div>{getStatusBadge(item.status)}</div>;
   }, (prev, next) => 
     prev.item.id === next.item.id &&
     prev.item.status === next.item.status &&
     prev.getStatusBadge === next.getStatusBadge
   );
   ItemCard.displayName = "ItemCard";
   ```

4. **Virtual Scrolling untuk Large Lists**
   - Gunakan `@tanstack/react-virtual` untuk list dengan ribuan item.
   - **ALWAYS** set `estimateSize` yang akurat untuk performa optimal.
   - **ALWAYS** use `overscan` untuk smooth scrolling.
   
   ✅ GOOD - Virtual scrolling pattern:
   ```tsx
   import { useVirtualizer } from "@tanstack/react-virtual";
   
   export function ItemsTab({ items }: Props) {
     const parentRef = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null);
     
     const virtualizer = useVirtualizer({
       count: items.length,
       getScrollElement: () => parentRef.current,
       estimateSize: () => 160, // Estimated height per item
       overscan: 5,
     });
     
     return (
       <div ref={parentRef} className="h-[600px] overflow-auto">
         <div style={{ height: `${virtualizer.getTotalSize()}px`, position: "relative" }}>
           {virtualizer.getVirtualItems().map((virtualItem) => {
             const item = items[virtualItem.index];
             return (
               <div
                 key={virtualItem.key}
                 style={{
                   position: "absolute",
                   top: 0,
                   left: 0,
                   width: "100%",
                   transform: `translateY(${virtualItem.start}px)`,
                 }}
               >
                 <ItemCard item={item} />
               </div>
             );
           })}
         </div>
       </div>
     );
   }
   ```

5. **Optimistic Updates di TanStack Query**
   - Implement `onMutate`, `onError`, `onSettled` untuk immediate UI feedback.
   - **ALWAYS** cancel queries dan save previous state untuk rollback.
   - **ALWAYS** invalidate queries di `onSuccess` untuk sync dengan server.
   
   ✅ GOOD - Optimistic update pattern:
   ```tsx
   export function useCreateItem() {
     const queryClient = useQueryClient();
     
     return useMutation({
       mutationFn: (data: CreateData) => itemService.create(data),
       onMutate: async (newItem) => {
         // Cancel outgoing queries
         await queryClient.cancelQueries({ queryKey: ["items"] });
         
         // Snapshot previous value
         const previousItems = queryClient.getQueriesData({ queryKey: ["items"] });
         
         // Optimistically update cache
         queryClient.setQueriesData({ queryKey: ["items"] }, (old: any) => {
           if (!old?.data) return old;
           return {
             ...old,
             data: {
               ...old.data,
               data: [{ id: Date.now(), ...newItem }, ...(old.data.data || [])],
               meta: { ...old.data.meta, pagination: { ...old.data.meta?.pagination, total: (old.data.meta?.pagination?.total || 0) + 1 } },
             },
           };
         });
         
         return { previousItems };
       },
       onError: (err, newItem, context) => {
         // Rollback on error
         if (context?.previousItems) {
           context.previousItems.forEach(([queryKey, data]) => {
             queryClient.setQueryData(queryKey, data);
           });
         }
       },
       onSuccess: () => {
         // Invalidate untuk sync dengan server
         queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ["items"] });
       },
     });
   }
   ```

6. **Debouncing untuk Search/Filter**
   - **ALWAYS** debounce search inputs untuk mengurangi API calls.
   - Gunakan `useDebounce` hook atau `lodash/debounce`.
   - Default delay: 300-500ms untuk search, 100-200ms untuk filter.
   
   ✅ GOOD - Debounced search:
   ```tsx
   import { useDebounce } from "@/hooks/use-debounce";
   
   export function useItemList() {
     const [search, setSearch] = useState("");
     const debouncedSearch = useDebounce(search, 300);
     
     const { data } = useQuery({
       queryKey: ["items", { search: debouncedSearch }],
       queryFn: () => itemService.list({ search: debouncedSearch }),
     });
     
     return { search, setSearch, data };
   }
   ```

7. **TanStack Query Configuration**
   - Set `staleTime` untuk mengurangi unnecessary refetches (default: 5 minutes untuk list data).
   - Set `gcTime` (garbage collection time) untuk cache retention (default: 10 minutes).
   - Enable `refetchOnMount` dan `refetchOnReconnect` untuk data freshness.
   
   ✅ GOOD - Optimal QueryClient config:
   ```tsx
   const queryClient = new QueryClient({
     defaultOptions: {
       queries: {
         staleTime: 5 * 60 * 1000, // 5 minutes
         gcTime: 10 * 60 * 1000, // 10 minutes (formerly cacheTime)
         refetchOnMount: true,
         refetchOnReconnect: true,
         refetchOnWindowFocus: false, // Disable untuk dashboard apps
       },
     },
   });
   ```

8. **useMemo untuk Expensive Calculations**
   - Gunakan `useMemo` untuk calculations yang expensive (filtering, sorting, mapping large arrays).
   - **ALWAYS** include all dependencies yang digunakan dalam calculation.
   - **NEVER** use `useMemo` untuk simple calculations (overhead lebih besar dari benefit).
   
   ✅ GOOD - Memoized expensive calculations:
   ```tsx
   // Expensive: mapping + filtering large array
   const itemsWithStringId = useMemo(
     () => items.map((item) => ({ ...item, id: item.id.toString() })),
     [items]
   );
   
   // Expensive: complex filtering + sorting
   const filteredAndSorted = useMemo(() => {
     return items
       .filter(item => item.status === statusFilter)
       .sort((a, b) => {
         if (sortOrder === "asc") return a[sortBy] - b[sortBy];
         return b[sortBy] - a[sortBy];
       });
   }, [items, statusFilter, sortBy, sortOrder]);
   ```

**React Hooks Performance Checklist:**
- [ ] Semua hooks dipanggil di top level component (sebelum early return)
- [ ] Tidak ada hooks di dalam JSX props atau conditional statements
- [ ] useCallback untuk function references yang digunakan di dependency arrays
- [ ] useMemo untuk expensive calculations dan stable references
- [ ] React.memo untuk components yang sering re-render dengan props stabil
- [ ] Virtual scrolling untuk lists dengan > 100 items
- [ ] Optimistic updates di mutations untuk immediate feedback
- [ ] Debouncing untuk search/filter inputs
- [ ] TanStack Query staleTime/gcTime configured optimal
- [ ] Dependency arrays stabil dan konsisten

Backend Standards (Go + Gin)
- Use layered architecture: Handler → Service → Repository.
- Use dependency injection pattern (constructor-based).
- Use interface-based design for repositories.
- Follow API response standards from `/docs/api-standart/`.
- All errors must use error codes from `/docs/api-standart/api-error-codes.md`.
- **CRITICAL**: Backend must be resilient against panic, retry storm, burst traffic, and dependency degradation.

Backend Panic/Crash Prevention (CRITICAL)
- Always keep `gin.Recovery()` enabled globally and return standardized error response with request ID.
- Never panic for expected runtime failures (validation, not found, conflict, timeout, dependency error).
- Validate query/body/path params with strict bounds before business logic (e.g., `page >= 1`, `1 <= per_page <= 100`).
- Enforce bounded resource usage:
  - Request body size limit (`http.MaxBytesReader` + Content-Length pre-check)
  - Multipart memory/body limits
  - DB pagination upper bound
- All remote/dependency calls must use timeout-bound contexts (DB/Redis/HTTP/external API/background workers).
- During graceful shutdown, stop all background workers before closing shared resources.
- Use row-level locking (`FOR UPDATE`) for concurrent mutation paths that can race.

Retry Storm / Burst Control (CRITICAL)
- Use distributed rate limiting (Redis-backed) for multi-instance environments.
- For production, limiter backend failure policy must be explicit and safe (prefer fail-closed for auth/public abuse surfaces).
- Add jittered exponential backoff for retries. Never use tight immediate retries.
- Cap retries and define retry budget per request/user/session.
- Do not retry non-idempotent mutations unless idempotency key is implemented.
- For idempotent write endpoints, support idempotency key to prevent duplicate effects under retries.
- Return `Retry-After` header for `429` or temporary overload scenarios when applicable.

Client Resilience / Anti-Crash (CRITICAL)
- API hooks/services must classify errors into: validation, auth, rate-limit, timeout, network, server.
- For `429`/`503`, respect `Retry-After` and show cooldown UI; do not auto-spam retries.
- TanStack Query defaults should avoid retry storms:
  - Disable retries for 4xx (except optional 408/409 strategy)
  - Limited retries for 5xx/network with exponential backoff + jitter
  - Use `staleTime` and deduping to reduce refetch bursts
- Prevent thundering herd on focus/reconnect by controlling `refetchOnWindowFocus` and staggered/manual refetch where needed.
- Always show safe fallback UI (loading/error/empty) and never assume nested response fields exist.
- **CRITICAL**: When adding/modifying backend endpoints:
  1. Update Postman collection: `/docs/postman/CRM-Healthcare-API.postman_collection.json`
  2. Update Postman documentation if needed: `/docs/postman/README.md` or `/docs/postman/SETUP.md`
  3. Test with Postman before marking as complete.

Sprint Management
- **CRITICAL**: When completing sprint tasks:
  1. Mark completed tasks in `/docs/SPRINT_PLANNING.md` with `[x]`
  2. Update acceptance criteria status if applicable
  3. Document any deviations or additional work done
- Do NOT create separate completion documents. Update `SPRINT_PLANNING.md` directly.

Naming & conventions
- Kebab-case directories, PascalCase components, camelCase functions/variables.
- Each folder can have an `index.ts` barrel only when it improves DX and tree-shaking.
- Keep files short and cohesive; extract when a file grows beyond one responsibility.

Component Logic Separation Examples

❌ BAD - Logic in component:
```tsx
export function LoginForm() {
  const [email, setEmail] = useState("");
  const [password, setPassword] = useState("");
  
  const handleSubmit = async () => {
    // Business logic in component - BAD!
    const response = await authService.login({ email, password });
    if (response.success) {
      useAuthStore.getState().setUser(response.data.user);
      router.push("/dashboard");
    }
  };
  
  return <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>...</form>;
}
```

✅ GOOD - Logic in hook:
```tsx
// hooks/useLogin.ts
export function useLogin() {
  const router = useRouter();
  const { login } = useAuthStore();
  
  return useMutation({
    mutationFn: (data: LoginFormData) => login(data.email, data.password),
    onSuccess: () => router.push("/dashboard"),
  });
}

// components/login-form.tsx
export function LoginForm() {
  const { register, handleSubmit, formState: { errors } } = useForm<LoginFormData>({
    resolver: zodResolver(loginSchema),
  });
  const { mutate: login, isPending } = useLogin();
  
  return <form onSubmit={handleSubmit((data) => login(data))}>...</form>;
}
```
